L01.excerpt: Thou still unravish'd bride of quietness,
L01.full_text: Thou still unravish'd bride of quietness,

L02.excerpt: Thou foster-child of silence and slow time,
L02.full_text: Thou foster-child of silence and slow time,

L03.excerpt: Sylvan historian, who canst thus express
L03.full_text: Sylvan historian, who canst thus express

L04.excerpt: A flowery tale more sweetly than our rhyme:
L04.full_text: A flowery tale more sweetly than our rhyme:

L05.excerpt: What leaf-fring'd legend haunts about thy shape
L05.full_text: What leaf-fring'd legend haunts about thy shape

L06.excerpt: Of deities or mortals, or of both,
L06.full_text: Of deities or mortals, or of both,

L07.excerpt: In Tempe or the dales of Arcady?
L07.full_text: In Tempe or the dales of Arcady?

L08.excerpt: What men or gods are these? What maidens loth?
L08.full_text: What men or gods are these? What maidens loth?

L09.excerpt: What mad pursuit? What struggle to escape?
L09.full_text: What mad pursuit? What struggle to escape?

L10.excerpt: What pipes and timbrels? What wild ecstasy?
L10.full_text: What pipes and timbrels? What wild ecstasy?

L11.excerpt: Heard melodies are sweet, but those unheard
L11.full_text: Heard melodies are sweet, but those unheard

L12.excerpt: Are sweeter; therefore, ye soft pipes, play on;
L12.full_text: Are sweeter; therefore, ye soft pipes, play on;

L13.excerpt: Not to the sensual ear, but, more endear'd,
L13.full_text: Not to the sensual ear, but, more endear'd,

L14.excerpt: Pipe to the spirit ditties of no tone:
L14.full_text: Pipe to the spirit ditties of no tone:

L15.excerpt: Fair youth, beneath the trees, thou canst not leave
L15.full_text: Fair youth, beneath the trees, thou canst not leave

L16.excerpt: Thy song, nor ever can those trees be bare;
L16.full_text: Thy song, nor ever can those trees be bare;

L17.excerpt: Bold Lover, never, never canst thou kiss,
L17.full_text: Bold Lover, never, never canst thou kiss,

L18.excerpt: Though winning near the goal yet, do not grieve;
L18.full_text: Though winning near the goal yet, do not grieve;

L19.excerpt: She cannot fade, though thou hast not thy bliss,
L19.full_text: She cannot fade, though thou hast not thy bliss,

L20.excerpt: For ever wilt thou love, and she be fair!
L20.full_text: For ever wilt thou love, and she be fair!

L21.excerpt: Ah, happy, happy boughs! that cannot shed
L21.full_text: Ah, happy, happy boughs! that cannot shed

L22.excerpt: Your leaves, nor ever bid the Spring adieu;
L22.full_text: Your leaves, nor ever bid the Spring adieu;

L24.excerpt: For ever piping songs for ever new;
L24.full_text: For ever piping songs for ever new;

L25.excerpt: More happy love! more happy, happy love!
L25.full_text: More happy love! more happy, happy love!

L26.excerpt: For ever warm and still to be enjoy'd,
L26.full_text: For ever warm and still to be enjoy'd,

L27.excerpt: For ever panting, and for ever young;
L27.full_text: For ever panting, and for ever young;

L28.excerpt: All breathing human passion far above,
L28.full_text: All breathing human passion far above,

L29.excerpt: That leaves a heart high-sorrowful and cloy'd,
L29.full_text: That leaves a heart high-sorrowful and cloy'd,

L30.excerpt: A burning forehead, and a parching tongue.
L30.full_text: A burning forehead, and a parching tongue.

L31.excerpt: Who are these coming to the sacrifice?
L31.full_text: Who are these coming to the sacrifice?

L32.excerpt: To what green altar, O mysterious priest,
L32.full_text: To what green altar, O mysterious priest,

L33.excerpt: Lead'st thou that heifer lowing at the skies,
L33.full_text: Lead'st thou that heifer lowing at the skies,

L34.excerpt: And all her silken flanks with garlands drest?
L34.full_text: And all her silken flanks with garlands drest?

L35.excerpt: What little town by river or sea shore,
L35.full_text: What little town by river or sea shore,

L37.excerpt: Is emptied of this folk, this pious morn?
L37.full_text: Is emptied of this folk, this pious morn?

L38.excerpt: And, little town, thy streets for evermore
L38.full_text: And, little town, thy streets for evermore

L39.excerpt: Will silent be; and not a soul to tell
L39.full_text: Will silent be; and not a soul to tell

L40.excerpt: Why thou art desolate, can e'er return.
L40.full_text: Why thou art desolate, can e'er return.

L41.excerpt: O Attic shape! Fair attitude! with brede
L41.full_text: O Attic shape! Fair attitude! with brede

L42.excerpt: Of marble men and maidens overwrought,
L42.full_text: Of marble men and maidens overwrought,

L43.excerpt: With forest branches and the trodden weed;
L43.full_text: With forest branches and the trodden weed;

L44.excerpt: Thou, silent form, dost tease us out of thought
L44.full_text: Thou, silent form, dost tease us out of thought

L46.excerpt: When old age shall this generation waste,
L46.full_text: When old age shall this generation waste,

L47.excerpt: Thou shalt remain, in midst of other woe
L47.full_text: Thou shalt remain, in midst of other woe

L48.excerpt: Than ours, a friend to man, to whom thou say'st,
L48.full_text: Than ours, a friend to man, to whom thou say'st,

L49.excerpt: "Beauty is truth, truth beauty,—that is all
L49.full_text: "Beauty is truth, truth beauty,—that is all

L50.excerpt: Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know."
L50.full_text: Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know."

text.canonical: true for one cell per line
